The **init** accessor in C# is a feature introduced in C# 9.0 that allows properties to be set only during object initialization, not afterward. Itâ€™s like a set accessor, but it locks the value after construction.

ğŸ”§ Syntax:
csharp
Copy
Edit
public class Person
{
    public string Name { get; init; }
}
âœ… Example Usage:
csharp
Copy
Edit
var person = new Person { Name = "Alice" };
Console.WriteLine(person.Name); // Output: Alice

// person.Name = "Bob"; âŒ Error: Cannot assign to init-only property
ğŸ§  Why use init?
Promotes immutability while keeping object initializers readable.

Prevents accidental modification after the object is constructed.

ğŸ’¡ Comparison: set vs init
Feature	set	init
Set in constructor or initializer	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes
Set after creation	âœ… Yes	âŒ No
Supports immutability	âŒ No	âœ… Yes

ğŸ”’ Works well with records:
csharp
Copy
Edit
public record Person
{
    public string Name { get; init; }
}
Records and init work together to create clean, immutable data models.




using System;

namespace InitPropertyExample
{
    class Student
    {
        public string Name { get; init; }
        public int RollNo { get; init; }
    }

    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            // Using init-only properties
            var student = new Student
            {
                Name = "Koustubh",
                RollNo = 101
            };

            Console.WriteLine($"Name: {student.Name}, RollNo: {student.RollNo}");

            // âŒ This will give a compile-time error:
            // student.Name = "New Name";
        }
    }
}

